content:
Last validator breaks 2 of the constraints. It has 16 factors (you said at most 15) and one factor x = 1 000 000 (you said x<1 000 000).

Also, it's the only test/validator that includes n itself as a factor that is a perfect square. You should really make it clear in the statement OR test cases that the number itself counts as a factor, because often in mathematics we look only at "proper factors" which do not include n itself.

Also, your test cases only go as high as n = 401, but then your validators go up to a million. That's a huge difference in tests and Validators.

Hi @adrianr : i got your CoC today and disappointed 75% -> Test case 4 !
In your statements, you say "factor x<1 000 000" => equality is not comprised ?
=> can you correct please ?

Agree with DrQuarius.
The number itself is still a problem as there is no visible test case for it. Only test 9 which is in fact a validator (so not visible by player during clash). So you need to state it clearly in the description and change a visible test case so people can test it during clash.
More the constraint says factor x < 1 000 000 which is obviously false (test 9 again)...
The real constraint is factor x <= n

Very bad problem statement, I'm surprised this was approved. Firstly ONE is a perfect square, so NONE of them should give -1 (even 0 has 1 as a factor, in fact every number is a factor of 0). Secondly, you don't specify HOW to print the factors. Space-separated is only clear on the LAST test case.
Thirdly, it wasn't clear whether the number itself is a factor (should have been stated).
This description is extremely lacking.

✅ Approved the contribution.

n=int(input())
a= [x for x in range(2,n+1) if n%x==0 and int(x**0.5)**2==x]or[-1]
